# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: spectral-methods-numerical
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/chebyshev-pseudospectral-method] The **Chebyshev pseudospectral method** for optimal control problems is based on Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/chebyshev-pseudospectral-method] It is part of the larger theory of pseudospectral optimal control, a term coined by Ross.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/chebyshev-pseudospectral-method] Unlike the Legendre pseudospectral method, the Chebyshev pseudospectral (PS) method does not immediately offer high-accuracy quadrature solutions.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/chebyshev-pseudospectral-method] Consequently, two different versions of the method have been proposed: one by Elnagar et al., and another by Fahroo and Ross.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/chebyshev-pseudospectral-method] The two versions differ in their quadrature techniques.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/chebyshev-pseudospectral-method] The Fahroo–Ross method is more commonly used today due to the ease in implementation of the Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature technique (in contrast to Elnagar–Kazemi's cell-averaging method).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/chebyshev-pseudospectral-method] In 2008, Trefethen showed that the Clenshaw–Curtis method was nearly as accurate as Gauss quadrature.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/chebyshev-pseudospectral-method] This breakthrough result opened the door for a covector mapping theorem for Chebyshev PS methods.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/chebyshev-pseudospectral-method] A complete mathematical theory for Chebyshev PS methods was finally developed in 2009 by Gong, Ross and Fahroo.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/chebyshev-pseudospectral-method] The Chebyshev PS method is frequently confused with other Chebyshev methods.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/chebyshev-pseudospectral-method] Prior to the advent of PS methods, many authors proposed using Chebyshev polynomials to solve optimal control problems; however, none of these methods belong to the class of pseudospectral methods.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] In mathematics, a **collocation method** is a method for the numerical solution of ordinary differential equations, partial differential equations and integral equations.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] The idea is to choose a finite-dimensional space of candidate solutions (usually polynomials up to a certain degree) and a number of points in the domain (called *collocation points*), and to select that solution which satisfies the given equation at the collocation points.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] This gives *n* + 1 conditions, which matches the *n* + 1 parameters needed to specify a polynomial of degree *n*.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] All these collocation methods are in fact implicit Runge–Kutta methods.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] The coefficients *c**k* in the Butcher tableau of a Runge–Kutta method are the collocation points.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] However, not all implicit Runge–Kutta methods are collocation methods.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] Pick, as an example, the two collocation points *c*1 = 0 and *c*2 = 1 (so *n* = 2).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] There are three conditions, so *p* should be a polynomial of degree 2.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] This method is known as the "trapezoidal rule" for differential equations.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] and approximating the integral on the right-hand side by the trapezoidal rule for integrals.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] The Gauss–Legendre methods use the points of Gauss–Legendre quadrature as collocation points.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] The Gauss–Legendre method based on *s* points has order 2*s*.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] All Gauss–Legendre methods are A-stable.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] In fact, one can show that the order of a collocation method corresponds to the order of the quadrature rule that one would get using the collocation points as weights.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] In direct collocation method, we are essentially performing variational calculus with the finite-dimensional subspace of piecewise linear functions (as in trapezoidal rule), or cubic functions, or other piecewise polynomial functions.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] In orthogonal collocation method, we instead use the finite-dimensional subspace spanned by the first N vectors in some orthogonal polynomial basis, such as the Legendre polynomials.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] Top F1 teams began switching from Quasi-Static simulation to collocation methods in 2010s to simulate the time it takes for a car to go around a circuit.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] It is thought that Sauber were one of the first teams to make this transition.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] Traditional Quasi-Static simulation involves the construction of a gLat-gLong-vCar performance envelope for the car, then starting at each apex (minimum car speed) and accelerating forwards, and backwards through the braking zone using this envelope to stitch a lap together.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] It is a gross simplification of the problem because the envelope is steady state so ignores any of the dynamics that occur, for example, the car can switch instantaneously between understeer and oversteer.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] The switch to collocation methods in simulation involved casting the entire lap as an optimisation problem, broken down by distance steps around the lap which describe the car physics at each point.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] The objective is to minimise laptime and error in the physics at each point.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] Once the optimisation is complete, the collocation method finds the minimum laptime for a particular car setup around a circuit by varying brake/throttle and steering wheel angle while obeying the physics at every point.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/collocation-method] This allows for extremely complex problems to be solved optimally.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] A **fast Fourier transform** (**FFT**) is an algorithm that computes the discrete Fourier transform (DFT), or its inverse (IDFT), of a sequence.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] A Fourier transform converts a signal from its original domain (often time or space) to a representation in the frequency domain and vice versa.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] The DFT is obtained by decomposing a sequence of values into components of different frequencies.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] This operation is useful in many fields, but computing it directly from the definition is often too slow to be practical.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] An FFT rapidly computes such transformations by factorizing the DFT matrix into a product of sparse (mostly zero) factors.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] As a result, it manages to reduce the complexity of computing the DFT from ${\textstyle O(n^{2})}$ , which arises if one simply applies the definition of DFT, to ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ , where n is the length of the sequence.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] The difference in speed can be enormous, especially for long sequences where n may be in the thousands or millions.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] As the FFT is merely an algebraic refactoring of terms within the DFT, the DFT and the FFT both perform mathematically equivalent and interchangeable operations, assuming that all terms are computed with infinite precision.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] However, in the presence of round-off error, many FFT algorithms are much more accurate than evaluating the DFT definition directly or indirectly.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] There are many different FFT algorithms based on a wide range of published theories, from simple complex-number arithmetic to group theory and number theory.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] The best-known FFT algorithms depend upon the factorization of n, but there are FFTs with $O(n\log n)$ complexity for all n, including prime values.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Many FFT algorithms depend only on the fact that ${\textstyle e^{-2\pi i/n}}$ is an nth primitive root of unity, and thus can be applied to analogous transforms over any finite field, such as number-theoretic transforms.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Since the inverse DFT is the same as the DFT, but with the opposite sign in the exponent and a 1/*n* factor, any FFT algorithm can easily be adapted for it.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Fast Fourier transforms are widely used for applications in engineering, music, science, and mathematics.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] The basic ideas were popularized in 1965, but some algorithms had been derived as early as 1805.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] In 1994, Gilbert Strang described the FFT as "the most important numerical algorithm of our lifetime", and it was included in Top 10 Algorithms of 20th Century by the IEEE magazine *Computing in Science & Engineering*.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] The development of fast algorithms for DFT was prefigured in Carl Friedrich Gauss's unpublished 1805 work on the orbits of asteroids Pallas and Juno.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Gauss wanted to interpolate the orbits from sample observations; his method was very similar to the one that would be published in 1965 by James Cooley and John Tukey, who are generally credited for the invention of the modern generic FFT algorithm.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] While Gauss's work predated even Joseph Fourier's 1822 results, he did not analyze the method's complexity, and eventually used other methods to achieve the same end.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Between 1805 and 1965, some versions of FFT were published by other authors.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Frank Yates in 1932 published his version called *interaction algorithm*, which provided efficient computation of Hadamard and Walsh transforms.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Yates' algorithm is still used in the field of statistical design and analysis of experiments.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Danielson and Cornelius Lanczos published their version to compute DFT for x-ray crystallography, a field where calculation of Fourier transforms presented a formidable bottleneck.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Good published a paper establishing the prime-factor FFT algorithm that applies to discrete Fourier transforms of size ${\textstyle n=n_{1}n_{2}}$ , where $n_{1}$ and $n_{2}$ are coprime.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] James Cooley and John Tukey independently rediscovered these earlier algorithms and published a more general FFT in 1965 that is applicable when n is composite and not necessarily a power of 2, as well as analyzing the ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ scaling.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Tukey came up with the idea during a meeting of President Kennedy's Science Advisory Committee, where a discussion topic involved detecting nuclear tests by the Soviet Union by setting up sensors to surround the country from outside.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] To analyze the output of these sensors, an FFT algorithm would be needed.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] In discussion with Tukey, Richard Garwin recognized the general applicability of the algorithm not just to national security problems, but also to a wide range of problems including one of immediate interest to him, determining the periodicities of the spin orientations in a 3-D crystal of Helium-3.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Garwin gave Tukey's idea to Cooley (both worked at IBM's Watson labs) for implementation.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Cooley and Tukey published the paper in a relatively short time of six months.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] As Tukey did not work at IBM, the patentability of the idea was doubted and the algorithm went into the public domain, which, through the computing revolution of the next decade, made FFT one of the indispensable algorithms in digital signal processing.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] where $e^{i2\pi /n}$ is a primitive nth root of 1.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Evaluating this definition directly requires ${\textstyle O(n^{2})}$ operations: there are n outputs Xk , and each output requires a sum of n terms.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] An FFT is any method to compute the same results in ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ operations.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] All known FFT algorithms require ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ operations, although there is no known proof that lower complexity is impossible.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] To illustrate the savings of an FFT, consider the count of complex multiplications and additions for ${\textstyle n=4096}$ data points.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Evaluating the DFT's sums directly involves ${\textstyle n^{2}}$ complex multiplications and ${\textstyle n(n-1)}$ complex additions, of which ${\textstyle O(n)}$ operations can be saved by eliminating trivial operations such as multiplications by 1, leaving about 30 million operations.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] By far the most commonly used FFT is the Cooley–Tukey algorithm.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] The best known use of the Cooley–Tukey algorithm is to divide the transform into two pieces of size *n*/2 at each step, and is therefore limited to power-of-two sizes, but any factorization can be used in general (as was known to both Gauss and Cooley/Tukey).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] These are called the *radix-2* and *mixed-radix* cases, respectively (and other variants such as the split-radix FFT have their own names as well).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Although the basic idea is recursive, most traditional implementations rearrange the algorithm to avoid explicit recursion.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Also, because the Cooley–Tukey algorithm breaks the DFT into smaller DFTs, it can be combined arbitrarily with any other algorithm for the DFT, such as those described below.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] For ${\textstyle n=n_{1}n_{2}}$ with coprime ${\textstyle n_{1}}$ and ${\textstyle n_{2}}$ , one can use the prime-factor (Good–Thomas) algorithm (PFA), based on the Chinese remainder theorem, to factorize the DFT similarly to Cooley–Tukey but without the twiddle factors.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Algorithms that recursively factorize the DFT into smaller operations other than DFTs include the Bruun and QFT algorithms.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] (The Rader–Brenner and QFT algorithms were proposed for power-of-two sizes, but it is possible that they could be adapted to general composite n.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Bruun's algorithm applies to arbitrary even composite sizes.) Bruun's algorithm, in particular, is based on interpreting the FFT as a recursive factorization of the polynomial $z^{n}-1$ , here into real-coefficient polynomials of the form $z^{m}-1$ and $z^{2m}+az^{m}+1$ .
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] In particular, Winograd also makes use of the PFA as well as an algorithm by Rader for FFTs of *prime* sizes.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Hexagonal fast Fourier transform (HFFT) aims at computing an efficient FFT for the hexagonally-sampled data by using a new addressing scheme for hexagonal grids, called Array Set Addressing (ASA).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] and efficient FFT algorithms have been designed for this situation (see e.g., Sorensen, 1987).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] One approach consists of taking an ordinary algorithm (e.g., Cooley–Tukey) and removing the redundant parts of the computation, saving roughly a factor of two in time and memory.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Alternatively, it is possible to express an *even*-length real-input DFT as a complex DFT of half the length (whose real and imaginary parts are the even/odd elements of the original real data), followed by $O(n)$ post-processing operations.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Bruun's algorithm (above) is another method that was initially proposed to take advantage of real inputs, but it has not proved popular.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] There are further FFT specializations for the cases of real data that have even/odd symmetry, in which case one can gain another factor of roughly two in time and memory and the DFT becomes the discrete cosine/sine transform(s) (DCT/DST).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Instead of directly modifying an FFT algorithm for these cases, DCTs/DSTs can also be computed via FFTs of real data combined with $O(n)$ pre- and post-processing.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] What is the lower bound on the complexity of fast Fourier transform algorithms?
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] A fundamental question of longstanding theoretical interest is to prove lower bounds on the complexity and exact operation counts of fast Fourier transforms, and many open problems remain.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] It is not rigorously proved whether DFTs truly require ${\textstyle \Omega (n\log n)}$ (i.e., order *$n\log n$* or greater) operations, even for the simple case of power of two sizes, although no algorithms with lower complexity are known.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] In particular, the count of arithmetic operations is usually the focus of such questions, although actual performance on modern-day computers is determined by many other factors such as cache or CPU pipeline optimization.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Following work by Shmuel Winograd (1978), a tight $\Theta (n)$ lower bound is known for the number of real multiplications required by an FFT.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] It can be shown that only ${\textstyle 4n-2\log _{2}^{2}(n)-2\log _{2}(n)-4}$ irrational real multiplications are required to compute a DFT of power-of-two length $n=2^{m}$ .
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Moreover, explicit algorithms that achieve this count are known (Heideman & Burrus, 1986; Duhamel, 1990).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] However, these algorithms require too many additions to be practical, at least on modern computers with hardware multipliers (Duhamel, 1990; Frigo & Johnson, 2005).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] A tight lower bound is not known on the number of required additions, although lower bounds have been proved under some restrictive assumptions on the algorithms.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] In 1973, Morgenstern proved an $\Omega (n\log n)$ lower bound on the addition count for algorithms where the multiplicative constants have bounded magnitudes (which is true for most but not all FFT algorithms).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Pan (1986) proved an $\Omega (n\log n)$ lower bound assuming a bound on a measure of the FFT algorithm's *asynchronicity*, but the generality of this assumption is unclear.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] A third problem is to minimize the *total* number of real multiplications and additions, sometimes called the *arithmetic complexity* (although in this context it is the exact count and not the asymptotic complexity that is being considered).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Again, no tight lower bound has been proven.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Since 1968, however, the lowest published count for power-of-two n was long achieved by the split-radix FFT algorithm, which requires ${\textstyle 4n\log _{2}(n)-6n+8}$ real multiplications and additions for *n* > 1.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] This was further reduced to ${\textstyle \sim {\frac {34}{9}}n\log _{2}n}$ (Johnson and Frigo, 2007; Lundy and Van Buskirk, 2007).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Most of the attempts to lower or prove the complexity of FFT algorithms have focused on the ordinary complex-data case, because it is the simplest.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] However, complex-data FFTs are so closely related to algorithms for related problems, such as real-data FFTs, discrete cosine transforms, discrete Hartley transforms, and so on, that any improvement in one of these would immediately lead to improvements in the others (Duhamel & Vetterli, 1990).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] All of the FFT algorithms discussed above compute the DFT exactly (i.e., neglecting floating-point errors).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] A few FFT algorithms have been proposed, however, that compute the DFT *approximately*, with an error that can be made arbitrarily small at the expense of increased computations.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Such algorithms trade the approximation error for increased speed or other properties.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] For example, an approximate FFT algorithm by Edelman et al.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] (1999) achieves lower communication requirements for parallel computing with the help of a fast multipole method.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] A wavelet-based approximate FFT by Guo and Burrus (1996) takes sparse inputs/outputs (time/frequency localization) into account more efficiently than is possible with an exact FFT.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Another algorithm for approximate computation of a subset of the DFT outputs is due to Shentov et al.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] The Edelman algorithm works equally well for sparse and non-sparse data, since it is based on the compressibility (rank deficiency) of the Fourier matrix itself rather than the compressibility (sparsity) of the data.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] FFT algorithms have errors when finite-precision floating-point arithmetic is used, but these errors are typically quite small; most FFT algorithms, e.g., Cooley–Tukey, have excellent numerical properties as a consequence of the pairwise summation structure of the algorithms.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] The upper bound on the relative error for the Cooley–Tukey algorithm is ${\textstyle O(\varepsilon \log n)}$ , compared to ${\textstyle O(\varepsilon n^{3/2})}$ for the naïve DFT formula, where 𝜀 is the machine floating-point relative precision.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] In fact, the root mean square (rms) errors are much better than these upper bounds, being only ${\textstyle O(\varepsilon {\sqrt {\log n}})}$ for Cooley–Tukey and ${\textstyle O(\varepsilon {\sqrt {n}})}$ for the naïve DFT (Schatzman, 1996).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] These results, however, are very sensitive to the accuracy of the twiddle factors used in the FFT (i.e. the trigonometric function values), and it is not unusual for incautious FFT implementations to have much worse accuracy, e.g. if they use inaccurate trigonometric recurrence formulas.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Some FFTs other than Cooley–Tukey, such as the Rader–Brenner algorithm, are intrinsically less stable.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] In fixed-point arithmetic, the finite-precision errors accumulated by FFT algorithms are worse, with rms errors growing as ${\textstyle O({\sqrt {n}})}$ for the Cooley–Tukey algorithm (Welch, 1969).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Achieving this accuracy requires careful attention to scaling to minimize loss of precision, and fixed-point FFT algorithms involve rescaling at each intermediate stage of decompositions like Cooley–Tukey.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] To verify the correctness of an FFT implementation, rigorous guarantees can be obtained in ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ time by a simple procedure checking the linearity, impulse-response, and time-shift properties of the transform on random inputs (Ergün, 1995).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] The values for intermediate frequencies may be obtained by various averaging methods.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Equivalently, it is the composition of a sequence of *d* sets of one-dimensional DFTs, performed along one dimension at a time (in any order).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] This compositional viewpoint immediately provides the simplest and most common multidimensional DFT algorithm, known as the **row-column** algorithm (after the two-dimensional case, below).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] That is, one simply performs a sequence of d one-dimensional FFTs (by any of the above algorithms): first you transform along the *n*1 dimension, then along the *n*2 dimension, and so on (actually, any ordering works).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] This method is easily shown to have the usual ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ complexity, where ${\textstyle n=n_{1}\cdot n_{2}\cdots n_{d}}$ is the total number of data points transformed.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] In more than two dimensions, it is often advantageous for cache locality to group the dimensions recursively.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] For example, a three-dimensional FFT might first perform two-dimensional FFTs of each planar slice for each fixed *n*1, and then perform the one-dimensional FFTs along the *n*1 direction.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Still, this remains a straightforward variation of the row-column algorithm that ultimately requires only a one-dimensional FFT algorithm as the base case, and still has $O(n\log n)$ complexity.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Yet another variation is to perform matrix transpositions in between transforming subsequent dimensions, so that the transforms operate on contiguous data; this is especially important for out-of-core and distributed memory situations where accessing non-contiguous data is extremely time-consuming.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] There are other multidimensional FFT algorithms that are distinct from the row-column algorithm, although all of them have ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ complexity.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Perhaps the simplest non-row-column FFT is the vector-radix FFT algorithm, which is a generalization of the ordinary Cooley–Tukey algorithm where one divides the transform dimensions by a vector ${\textstyle \mathbf {r} =\left(r_{1},r_{2},\ldots ,r_{d}\right)}$ of radices at each step.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] (This may also have cache benefits.) The simplest case of vector-radix is where all of the radices are equal (e.g., vector-radix-2 divides *all* of the dimensions by two), but this is not necessary.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Vector radix with only a single non-unit radix at a time, i.e. ${\textstyle \mathbf {r} =\left(1,\ldots ,1,r,1,\ldots ,1\right)}$ , is essentially a row-column algorithm.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Other, more complicated, methods include polynomial transform algorithms due to Nussbaumer (1977), which view the transform in terms of convolutions and polynomial products.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] See Duhamel and Vetterli (1990) for more information and references.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] A spherical-harmonic algorithm with ${\textstyle O(n^{2}\log n)}$ complexity is described by Rokhlin and Tygert.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] The fast folding algorithm is analogous to the FFT, except that it operates on a series of binned waveforms rather than a series of real or complex scalar values.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Rotation (which in the FFT is multiplication by a complex phasor) is a circular shift of the component waveform .
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Various groups have also published FFT algorithms for non-equispaced data, as reviewed in Potts *et al.* (2001).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Such algorithms do not strictly compute the DFT (which is only defined for equispaced data), but rather some approximation thereof (a non-uniform discrete Fourier transform, or NDFT, which itself is often computed only approximately).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] More generally, there are various other methods of spectral estimation.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] The FFT is used in digital recording, sampling, additive synthesis and pitch correction software.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] The FFT's importance derives from the fact that it has made working in the frequency domain equally computationally feasible as working in the temporal or spatial domain.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] In modern wireless communication standards, the FFT is a critical component for processing signals.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] Specifically, it is utilized in Orthogonal frequency-division multiplexing (OFDM) systems, such as 4G LTE and 5G NR.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] The efficiency of the FFT allows for high-speed data transmission by dividing a wideband signal into multiple closely spaced orthogonal subcarriers.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] This technology is essential for reducing interference and optimizing power consumption in mobile devices.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] The FFT can be a poor choice for analyzing signals with non-stationary frequency content—where the frequency characteristics change over time.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] DFTs provide a global frequency estimate, assuming that all frequency components are present throughout the entire signal, which makes it challenging to detect short-lived or transient features within signals.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] For cases where frequency information appears briefly in the signal or generally varies over time, alternatives like the short-time Fourier transform, discrete wavelet transforms, or discrete Hilbert transform can be more suitable.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/fast-fourier-transform] These transforms allow for localized frequency analysis by capturing both frequency and time-based information.
