[src:spectral-methods-numerical/spectral-element-method] In the numerical solution of partial differential equations, a topic in mathematics, the **spectral element method** (SEM) is a formulation of the finite element method (FEM) that uses high-degree piecewise polynomials as basis functions.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/spectral-element-method] The spectral element method was introduced in a 1984 paper by A.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/spectral-element-method] The spectral method expands the solution in trigonometric series, a chief advantage being that the resulting method is of a very high order.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/spectral-element-method] This approach relies on the fact that trigonometric polynomials are an orthonormal basis for $L^{2}(\Omega )$ .
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/spectral-element-method] The spectral element method chooses instead a high degree piecewise polynomial basis functions, also achieving a very high order of accuracy.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/spectral-element-method] Such polynomials are usually orthogonal Chebyshev polynomials or very high order Lagrange polynomials over non-uniformly spaced nodes.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/spectral-element-method] In SEM computational error decreases exponentially as the order of approximating polynomial increases, therefore a fast convergence of solution to the exact solution is realized with fewer degrees of freedom of the structure in comparison with FEM.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/spectral-element-method] In structural health monitoring, FEM can be used for detecting large flaws in a structure, but as the size of the flaw is reduced there is a need to use a high-frequency wave.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/spectral-element-method] In order to simulate the propagation of a high-frequency wave, the FEM mesh required is very fine resulting in increased computational time.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/spectral-element-method] On the other hand, SEM provides good accuracy with fewer degrees of freedom.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/spectral-element-method] Non-uniformity of nodes helps to make the mass matrix diagonal, which saves time and memory and is also useful for adopting a central difference method (CDM).
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/spectral-element-method] The disadvantages of SEM include difficulty in modeling complex geometry, compared to the flexibility of FEM.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/spectral-element-method] Although the method can be applied with a modal piecewise orthogonal polynomial basis, it is most often implemented with a nodal tensor product Lagrange basis.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/spectral-element-method] The method gains its efficiency by placing the nodal points at the Legendre-Gauss-Lobatto (LGL) points and performing the Galerkin method integrations with a reduced Gauss-Lobatto quadrature using the same nodes.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/spectral-element-method] With this combination, simplifications result such that mass lumping occurs at all nodes and a collocation procedure results at interior points.
[src:spectral-methods-numerical/spectral-element-method] The most popular applications of the method are in computational fluid dynamics and modeling seismic wave propagation.
